Yes, there are several other tools available that you can use to record and repeat actions on Linux. Here are some examples:

AutoKey: AutoKey is a free and open-source automation tool that allows you to automate repetitive tasks by recording and replaying mouse clicks and keyboard actions. It also offers a simple scripting language for more complex automation tasks. AutoKey is available in most Linux distribution repositories.

SikuliX: SikuliX is a powerful automation tool that uses image recognition to automate GUI interactions. It allows you to write automation scripts using a combination of Python and graphical elements, such as screenshots of UI elements. SikuliX is available for Linux, Windows, and macOS.

Robot Framework: Robot Framework is a generic test automation framework that allows you to write test cases using a simple keyword-driven syntax. It supports various automation libraries and tools, including Selenium for web automation and Appium for mobile automation. Robot Framework is open-source and available for Linux, Windows, and macOS.

PyAutoGUI: PyAutoGUI is a cross-platform GUI automation library for Python that allows you to control the mouse and keyboard to automate GUI interactions. It can also take screenshots, locate and control GUI elements, and perform other automation tasks. PyAutoGUI is open-source and available for Linux, Windows, and macOS.

These are just a few examples of the many tools available for automating repetitive tasks on Linux. You can choose the one that best suits your needs based on your requirements and level of expertise.





